list.item:
The subjunctive, in its simplest and apparently most primitive use, seen in Homer (284), expresses futurity, like the future indicative, and has ou) for its negative. E.g.,
*ou) ga/r pw toi/ous i)/don a)ne/ras ou)de\ i)/dwmai, for never did I see such men nor shall I ever see them, Il. i. 262 ;
kai/ pote/ tis ei)/ph|sin, and some one will some time say, Il. vi. 459.

div2.p:
Here again we see what the change is, for we represent it by
                            our change from is to was, have to had, shall and
                                will to should and would, etc.; as le/gei o(/ti a)lhqe/s e)stin,
                                he says that it is true;
                            e)/lecen o(/ti a)lhqe\s
                            ei)/h (or e)sti/n),
                                he said that it was true;
                            le/gei o(/ti gra/yei, he says that he will write;
                            e)/lecen o(/ti gra/yoi (or
                                gra/yei), he said that he would write. So ou)k oi)=da ti/ ei)/pw, I know not what I shall say;
                            ou)k h)/|dein ti/ ei)/poimi
                            (or ei)/pw), I knew not what I should say.

The present indicative represents an action as going on at the time of speaking or writing;
                            as gra/fw, I write, or I am
                                writing.

(a) The perfect of many verbs has the signification of a
                            present, which may usually be explained by the peculiar meaning of the
                            verbs. Thus qnh/|skein,
                                to die, teqnhke/nai, to be
                                dead;
                            kalei=n, to call, keklh=sqai, to be called or
                                named;
                            gi/gnesqai, to become, gegone/nai, to be;
                            mimnh/|skein, to remind, memnh=sqai, to
                                remember;
                            ei)de/nai, to know;
                            i(sta/nai, to place, e(sta/nai, to
                            stand. So bebhke/nai, to stand;
                            e)gnwke/nai, to know;
                            h)mfie/sqai, to wear;
                            kekth=sqai, to possess;
                            pepoiqe/nai, to trust;
                            pefuke/nai, to be (by nature); etc.

The present and aorist here differ only in this, that the present expresses an action in its duration, that is, as going on or repeated, while the aorist expresses simply its occurrence, the time of both tenses being otherwise precisely the same. E.g.
*)ea\n poih=| tou=to, if he shall be doing this, or if he shall do this (habitually);
e)a\n poih/sh| tou=to, (simply) if he shall do this;
ei) poioi/h tou=to, if he should be doing this, or if he should do this (habitually);
ei) poih/seie tou=to, if he should do this;
poi/ei tou=to, do this (habitually);
poi/hson tou=to, do this.
*ou(/tw nikh/saimi/ t' e)gw\ kai\ nomizoi/mhn sofo/s, on this condition may I gain the victory (aorist) and be considered (present) wise.
AR. Nub. 520. *bou/letai tou=to poiei=n , he wishes to do this (habitually);
bou/letai tou=to poih=sai, (simply) he wishes to do this. For other examples see below.

(As Present.) The present infinitive in indirect discourse generally represents a present indicative of the direct form. E.g.
*fhsi\ gra/fein, he says that he is writing;
e)/fh gra/fein, he said that he was writing;
fh/sei gra/fein, he will say that he is (then) writing. (In all three cases he says gra/fw.)
*)arrwstei=n profasi/zetai, he pretends that he is sick;
e)cw/mosen a)rrwstei=n toutoni/, he took his oath that this man was sick. DEM. xix. 124.
*ou)k e)/fh au)to\s a)ll' e)kei=non strathgei=n he said that not he himself, but Nicias, was general; i.e. he said ou)k e)gw\ au)to\s a)ll' e)kei=nos strathgei=. THUC. iv. 28.
See other examples under 683.

The first person of the subjunctive is used in questions of appeal, where the speaker asks
                            himself or another what he is to do. The
                            negative is mh/. In Attic
                            Greek this subjunctive is often introduced by bou/lei or bou/lesqe, sometimes in poetry by qe/leis or qe/lete. E.g. *ei)/pw tou=to;
                             shall I say this? or bou/lei ei)/pw tou=to;
                             do you wish that I should say this?
                            *mh\ tou=to poiw=men (or
                                poih/swmen); shall we not do this?
                            *ti/ ei)/pw; or ti/ bou/lesqe ei)/pw;
                             what shall I say? or what do you want me to say?

So with keleu/ete: *)alla\ pw=s;
                                ei)/pw keleu/ete kai\ ou)k o)rgiei=sqe;
                             do you command me to speak, and will you not be angry?
                            DEM. ix. 46.

*ei)/ tis kle/ptoi,
                                e)kola/zeto, if (ever) any one stole, he
                                was (in all such cases) punished;
                            ei)/ tis pra/ssoi (or pra/ceie) toiou=to/n ti, e)xalepai/nomen au)tw=|,
                                if (ever)
                                any one did such a thing, we were (always) angry with him;
                            ei)/ tis tou/tou pi/oi,
                                a)pe/qnh|sken, if any one
                                (ever) drank of
                                this, he died. (See 462.)

In the lyric and elegiac poets, as in Homer, the form with a)/n or ke/ was in good use in these sentences. See
PIND. Py. i. 100 o(\s a)\n e)gku/rsh| ,
v. 65 oi(=s a)\n e)qe/lh| ;
MIMN. ii. 9,
MIMN. iii. 1 e)ph\n paramei/yetai ;
SOL. xiii. 75;
THEOGN. 405,
SOL. 406 a(\ me\n h)=| kaka\, . . . a(\ d' a)\n h)=| xrh/sima . (For ordinary protasis see 469 and 470.) In the dramatists the relative with a)/n is completely established with the subjunctive as the regular form (like e)a/n, etc.) in both general and particular conditions. (See 471.)

(a) after primary tenses, each
                            verb retains both the mood and the tense of the direct discourse, no
                            change being made except (when necessary) in the person of the verb;

1. After primary tenses the verb
                            stands in the indicative, in the tense of the direct discourse. E.g.
                                *le/gei o(/ti gra/fei,
                                he says that he is writing;
                            le/gei o(/ti e)/grafen,
